name: Patrice Pottier
title: Divergence of thermal physiological traits in terrestrial breeding frogs along a tropical elevational gradient
comment_sampling: Geographical coordinates were not clearly reported. Only the location of some key Peruvian study sites were presented, but it was impossible to assign each site to a particular species. However, geographical coordinates are provided for the same species (and most likely for the same population in Rohr et al. 2018 (data from Catenazzi et al. 2014). The midpoint elevation was taken from Tab S3.
notes_acclimation: acclimation_time was taken as the mean of the range presented (2-3 days). Acclimation temperature was 16-21C so we taken the mean acclimation temperature and used SD_acclimation_temp was the variation around that mean
notes_test: NA
notes_UTL: n_HT was approximated as the total number of individuals tested (768) divided by the number of species tested (22) and rounded down.

comment_sampling: Sampling dates were taken as between June 1972 and June 1973 because this species breeding season is between June and August (see Tab 1) and the values reported represent the largest range of dates possible for this species. notes_test: SVL was reported as in Rohr et al. 2018.
notes_UTL: Data was digitised from figure 5 because Rohr et al. 2018 did not report SD.

name: Patrice Pottier
title: Critical Thermal Maximum as a Function of Temperature of Acclimation in Two Species of Hylid Frogs
comment_sampling: Sampling dates were between August 11 and August 23. Coordinates were taken from Rohr et al. 2018
notes_acclimation: Animals were acclimated for periods of 3 to 7 days, with most animals having 5-day acclimation periods.
notes_test: The endpoint was "the temperature at which no further movements of throat, abdomen, or limbs could be elicited by tapping the container against the wall of the beaker for 10 sec"
notes_UTL: Data was taken from Tab 4 because Rohr et al. 2018 did not report SD. Variance was converted to standard deviation.

title: Adaptations of the Reed Frog Hyperolius viridiflavus (Amphibia, Anura, Hyperoliidae) to its Arid Environment. IV. Ecological significance of Water Economy with Comments onThermoregulation and Energy Allocation
comment_sampling: Animals were received from a commercial supplier but were bred in the laboratory. Therefore, the origin was taken as "lab".

name: Patrice Pottier
title: Heat tolerance and thyroid activity in developing tadpoles and juvenile adults of xenopus laevis daudin
comment_sampling: NA
notes_acclimation: Animals were acclimated from the embryonic stage to the larval stage.
notes_test: gosner_tested was estimated based on the description of the stages (Nieuwkoop and Faber 1956) described in the paper. The n_animals_per_replicate was 30 at 36 degrees, and 50 animals at the other temperatures.
notes_UTL: LT50 was calculated using survival data digitised from figure 1. I fitted a logistic regression and used the dose.p() function from 'MASS' to calculate LT50. n_HT was taken as the n_test_temp

name: Patrice Pottier
title: Evidence for a Daily Rhythm of Heat Resistance in the Cricket Frog, Acris crepitans
notes_ID: Data for animals tested at 0130hr and acclimated to 4C
comment_sampling: Geographical coordinates were estimated using Google maps, by measuring a point 12 miles North and 9 miles W of Vermillion, Clay County, South Dakota. Elevation was estimated using https://latlongdata.com/elevation/
notes_acclimation: Acclimation_time was taken as the mean of the range presented (3-5 days)
notes_test: SVL was reported as in Rohr et al. 2018 for this species. The endpoint was "the temperature at which no further movements of throat, abdomen, or limbs could be elicited by tapping the container against the wall of the beaker for 10 sec"
notes_UTL: Data was digitised from figure 1. 95% confidence intervals were converted to se by dividing them by 1.96

name: Patrice Pottier
title: Variação latitudinal nos limites de tolerância e plasticidade térmica em anfíbios em um cenário de mudanças climáticas: efeito dos micro-habitats, sazonalidade e filogenia
chapter_title: Latitudinal variation of thermal tolerance limits and vulnerability to extreme temperatures in amphibians: the effects of microhabitats, seasonality and phylogeny
notes_ID: Note that data for some species was already presented in Gutiérrez-Pesquera et al 2016

name: Nayelli Rivera
title: Una valoración macrofisiológica de la vulnerabilidad al calentamiento global. Análisis de los límites de tolerancia térmica en comunidades de anfibios en gradientes latitudinales y altitudinales
notes_ID: population_ID was considered the same as in Pintanel (2018) because animals were collected in the same location
comment_sampling: It is specified that some species were obtained from a local lab and the rest of the species were sampled in ponds (it does not say which species were from the local lab or ponds). title: Standardized ethograms and a device for assessing amphibian thermal responses in a warming world
comment_sampling: Animals were sampled from 19°15'02"N to 19°34'04"N (latitude) and 96°59'44"W to 96°49'13"W (longitude). The midpoint of these coordinates was taken here.

notes_test: The endpoint was the complete immobility and rigidity of the body of the animals. name: Rachel Oh
title: Preferred Temperature, Avoidance Temperature and Lethal Temperature of Tadpoles of the Common Giant Toad ( Bufo gargarizans) and the Chinese Forest Frog ( Rana chensinensis)
notes_ID: population_ID was considered the same as in Wang and Li (2007) because animals were collected in the same location
comment_sampling: Tadpoles were collected from a pond at the northern side of the Qinling (??) Mountains, which seems to correspond to the coordinates provided in Wang_2014.
notes_test: Age tested was taken as the age of the tadpoles when collected (20 days) + the duration of acclimation (3 weeks)

name: Patrice Pottier
title: Allele-specific expression and gene regulation help explain transgressive thermal tolerance in non-native hybrids of the endangered California tiger salamander (Ambystoma californiense)
comment_sampling: NA
notes_acclimation:
The temperature of acclimation was not reported in the study but authors were contacted and they indicated that "Our animals were kept in a room that simulated the monthly temperatures of Jepson Prairie (California, USA). 
The mean monthly temperature regime was:
Jan: 9 °C
Feb: 10 °C
March: 12.5 °C
April: 17.5 °C
May: 20.5 °C 
June: 25.5 °C
July: 27.5 °C 
August: 27 °C 
September: 24 °C 
October: 19.5 °C 
November: 14.5 °C 
December: 10.5 °C 

Specifically we conducted the CTMax experiment in January / February, so they were acclimated to about 9-10 degrees C in the weeks before they were assayed."
notes_test: The ramping rate was not presented in the study
notes_UTL: Data was taken from the results section. Note that data from hybrids was not collected.
